dynamics underlying EAD generation. In reduced models, multiple ionic currents are lumped together, and thus, the full richness of the kinetics and interactions of the variety of currents present in cardiac cells are not captured. To explore the effect of circadian variation of L-type calcium current in a more biophysically detailed model, we performed simulations with the O’Hara-Rudy (ORd) model of the human ventricular AP (37). This model incorporates 12 distinct ionic currents: sodium, L-type calcium, transient outward potassium, rapid delayed rectiﬁer potassium, slow delayed rectiﬁer potassium, inward rectiﬁer potassium, sodium-calcium exchange, sodium-potassium ATPase, sarcolemmal calcium pump, sodium background, calcium background, and potassium background. The model also includes diffusion ﬂuxes of Naþ, Kþ, and Ca2þ from the submembrane space to the myoplasm, sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR) calcium release ﬂux via ryanodine receptors, calcium uptake via SERCA pumps, and calcium translocation from network SR to junctional SR compartments. The ORd model of L-type calcium current is based on experimental data from undiseased human ventricular myocytes and includes both voltage-dependent inactivation and calcium-dependent inactivation based on Ca2þ-calmodulin protein kinase kinetics. The maximal L-type current density is modeled using the Goldman-Hodgkin-Katz current equation:

